//satellite information "The NSU apparatus carries the payload of the Skobeltsyn Research Institute of Nuclear Physics of Moscow State University for monitoring heliogeophysical parameters of near-earth space in the interests of Roshydromet and additional target equipment of the Information Satellite Systems Joint-Stock Company a set of promising commutation boards of the SpaceWire format.

ISS JSC is testing the boards to confirm the possibility of their flight qualification as part of the CubeSat satellites and further integration of the equipment into the federal spacecraft. 

MCA "NORBI" was launched within the framework of the program of the state corporation "Roscosmos" "UniverSat".The program allows launching small spacecraft developed by Russian universities and research centers, taking into account the payload requirements of the Roscosmos state corporation. 

SMKA "NORBI" is assembled on the basis of a universal modular satellite platform developed at the OAI NSU within the framework of the project of the Federal Target Program of the Ministry of Education and Science of the Russian Federation for 2017‚Äì2019. The platform was developed jointly with the university's industrial partner OKB "Fifth Generation". 

The device got its name in honor of the unique little robot Norby from the cycle of stories for children of the same name by the famous science fiction writer Isaac Asimov. The name of the robot is an anagram of the name of the writer's daughter, Robin." "FEES (Flexible Experimental Embedded Satellite) is a self funded, collaborative project by the Italian GP Advanced Projects aimed at developing a low cost platform for In Orbit Testing and Validation of Electronics components. 

The whole satellite, including the electronics boards, is entirely design and manufactured within the project. The flight will be also the validation of this platform and components. The 0.3 kg satellite is built to a 0.3UCubeSat (10 cm √ó 10 cm √ó 3 cm) form factor. 

FEES Mission had three main goals. First of all, we aimed to obtain an in-orbit qualification of both an attitude determination architecture and a commercial GPS receiver. FEES also validated the exploitation of IRIDIUM global network to receive data, testing and supporting on-board traditional radio transmissions, which allowed us to manage the mission without a direct link to ground station and receiving early notifications. Finally, we meant to test a low cost UHF receivers with advanced modulation protocols." "The nanosatellites were built at the research laboratory of Ariel University, Israel, under the direction of Prof. Boaz Ben Moshe and by students from various departments of the university. 

The purpose of the satellites is to promote and make accessible research activities on the "new space" and provide a research platform for other research institutions and universities. Both satellites contain several scientific experiments such as a star tracking system, an aircraft tracking system, preparations for a laser communication stabilization system - Free Space Optical (FSO), photography and image analysis, and various other experiments. The size of the satellite is about 14X5X5 cm and its mass is about 300 grams. 

SATLLA-2A and SATLLA-2B will transmit a signal via amateur radio with their position in orbit and data from their sensors (battery status, gyros, temperatures, GPS). Both satellites are capable of relaying short messages via amateur radio." "FEES2 (Flexible Experimental Embedded Satellite2) is an evolution of FEES1, devoted to data relay testing in LoRa. 

The whole satellite, including the electronics boards, weights 0.3 kg and is built to a 0.3UCubeSat (10 cm √ó 10 cm √ó 3 cm) form factor. The configuration includes two independent radio modules which can transmit and receive respectively in VHF and UHF bands. FEES2 is the smallest satellite ever delivered from the ISS.. 

FEES2 Mission has the goal of understanding the required equipment and power levels to successfully execute a packet transmission to a satellite, and this will be made possible allowing the reception of LoRa packets in VHF and UHF bands and its retransmission (limited in length) within the UHF beacon. In addition, being delivered from the ISS, FEES2 will inherit its orbital characteristics, allowing to understand possible impacts of altitude and sun/eclipse cycles on such small pico-platforms." "FOSSASAT-2E is a 2P (10x5x5cm, 600g) Picosatellite manufactured by FOSSA Systems which provides IoT LoRa connectivity and is part of an 80-satellite constellation being launched by 2024. Several satellites are dedicated to experiments and specific projects, such as earth observation or others. 

Based on the PocketQube platform, this system of 5x5x5cm and 250g units hugely reduces the current cost for access to space. 

Base model features a GNSS receiver, GFSK, LoRa and S-BAND communications, an ARM STM32 Processor with 512Mb of flash, a high-efficieny MPPT based EPS with a regulated 3.3V common bus and 9W of solar power in direct sunlight. 

FOSSA is currently undergoing initial testing of these satellites and will soon open up the beacons with the first over the air update, for amateurs to decode. We will also allow packet retransmission and other experiments as we evaluate the capacities of the satellites." "FOSSASAT-2E is a 2P (10x5x5cm, 600g) Picosatellite manufactured by FOSSA Systems which provides IoT LoRa connectivity and is part of an 80-satellite constellation being launched by 2024. Several satellites are dedicated to experiments and specific projects, such as earth observation or others. 

