The satellite is built with low-budget, easily accessible parts in mind. It is equipped with an over-the-counter Arduino board for on-board data handling, a Ham radio based Arduino add-on for communication, and a camera for photo capture all while being powered by simple AA batteries. SBUDNIC will be sending telemetry data and photos from orbit during its mission life. The temperature sensors onboard will allow the satellite to record rudimentary temperature data at orbit altitude, and the camera will periodically capture and send photos in orbit. Since one of the goals of SBUDNIC is to make space exploration more accessible, anyone will be able to access the downlink and receive data and status updates through the satellite. 

